data.name: TextBox5.Text
data.value: The three colours chosen in this tab will determine the colours used to display elevations accross the grid. the minimum and maximum values of your chosen grid will be determined and will represent the top and bottom colours, with the central colour as a midpoint. To test what image a selection of colours will produce press the preview button.

data.name: TextBox8.Text
data.value: There is no limit to the size of the grid which can be processed .By only loading the data required at the time the cross section is drawn the application normally only requests approximately 20 – 100kb of data at a time, keeping load times very quick. If subsequent cross sections are drawn over areas where the grid has already been loaded then nothing extra has to be pulled in.

data.name: TextBox6.Text
data.value:
Requires 6 grid squares to be loaded. Each square is 5kb (for example) : 5 * 6 = 30kb of data
Requires less data to be loaded, however, subsequent cross sections are more likely to need to request a "Load". High overhead of requesting 6 "Loads"

data.name: TextBox7.Text
data.value:
Requires 3 grid squares to be loaded. Each square is 20kb (for example) : 20 * 3 = 60kb of data
Requires more data to be loaded, however, subsequent cross sections are less likely to need to request a "Load". Low overhead of only requesting 3 "Loads"

data.name: TextBox12.Text
data.value:
This option lets you pick a background image to drap over your grid.
For example, this could be a background map showing non-topographic information. It is important to note that the image MUST be cover the EXACT same area as the grid. this is because no matter what size image you choose it will be streched to fit the grid.

data.name: TextBox14.Text
data.value:
The extra options set here will determine what "tabs" will be shown in the final file and what user customizable options will be available in them
Display Table When enabled this option will enable the "Table" tab which displays the data behind the currently displayed cross section. Disable this option if you do not want users to be able to copy/paste the infomation out of the file. With this enabled the cross section data can be copy/pasted into excel or similar.
Changable Sample Sizes Enabling this option will display the "Options" tab including a list of pre-set sample sizes which you can set here. Sample sizes are restricted to values between 5 and 200
Plot Sample Points When using smaller sample sizes it's often helpfull to known the exact place the grid values were taken from. This option will place two buttons in the "Options" tab, "Plot Samples Ponits" which will display where the samples were taken on the map in the form of small black points. The other button "Clear Points" will remove all points from the map.

data.name: TextBox16.Text
data.value:
Partialy overlapping grids will work in the same way, however, where a grid value is not present (i.e. on the smaller grid) a "Null" value will be returned which will be displayed on the cross section as -9999, rendering the rest of the section almost impossible to read. Despite this any values returned will be correct and can be copy/pasted out of the file through the "Table" tab (if enabled) and copied to Excel or similar.
Legends are handled automaticly, series names are taken from the ASCII file name.

data.name: TextBox15.Text
data.value: You can compare multiple grids that cover the same area. For example a DTM (Digital Terrain Model) can be underlain by a DSM (Digital Surface Model) so when a cross section is drawn it shows the profile of both grids. In the case of the above example the DSM would show the heights of trees, buildings etc... whereas the DTM would show only the ground level, allowing a direct comparison.
